entry.title: Forward Capture process frame drops to Renderer process.
entry.content:
The MediaStreamTrack is currently unaware of what the camera's frame

rate is, because if a frame is dropped in the Capture process this is

never forwarded to the track. This is a problem for the implementation

of the MediaStreamTrack Statistics API, which currently counts delivered

frames correctly but not dropped frames.



The MediaStreamTrackImpl aims to count all frames that are dropped, but

is currently only aware of frames that were dropped in the Renderer

process. These frame drops are signalled to the Browser process'

VideoCaptureController where UMAs are counted.



The VideoCaptureController also received signals about frame drops in

the Capture process. This CL makes the controller forward frame drops

that originated in the Capture process to the Renderer process (but does

not forward frame drops that happened in the Renderer process, since the

Renderer process is already aware of these).



See diagram: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/attachment?aid=613344&signed_aid=qgr6SdlcmdfuTpNMqHyzFQ==&inline=1



In the future, when MediaStreamTrackImpl is aware of all frame drops,

we can move the UMAs to MediaStreamTrackImpl and delete the frame drop

callbacks that are reported from Renderer -> Browser processes. This

would make all frame drop signals go in a single direction:

Capture -> Browser -> Renderer



In a follow-up CL we will continue to plumb the frame drop signal until

it reaches MediaStreamTrackImpl.

entry.title: [iOS] Fix invariant on SignInAndHistorySyncCoordinator interruption
entry.content:
SigninCoordinator expects the identity in the completion info (argument

of the coordinator completion call back) to be nil if the coordinator

was interrupted before the sign-in flow is completed. And it should be

the case even if a sign-in is finished. (for instance in

TwoScreensSigninCoordinator).



However, the new SignInAndHistorySyncCoordinator uses the signed-in

identity instead of nil in this case, which triggers the

DCHECK in SigninCoordinator's runCompletionCallbackWithSigninResult.



To keep consistency with existing Signincoordinator, this CL set the

identity to nil during interruption.

entry.title: [mullet m2] Save profile changes and re-open the Autofill prompt.
entry.content:
User changes should be saved to the existing Autofill profile after the

"Save" button is clicked. The Autofill prompt should be opened again

after the user closes the edit dialog by clicking either "Cancel" or

"Save button.



Reopening the Autofill popup relies on the fact that the editor callback

is invoked when the editor dialog window is closed. If the Autofill

profile is going to be updated through the PersonalDataManager, the

caller must make sure the Autofill popup is triggered only once the

update is finished as it's an async task. This is achieved by adding

a PersonalDataManagerObserver to the PersonalDataManager and reopening

the prompt only once the update process has finished.



ContentAutofillDriver::RendererShouldTriggerSuggestions is invoked to

make the renderer process reopen the Autofill prompt. This is done to

ensure that the suggestions are regenerated from scratch and the regular

code path is used to trigger the popup.

entry.title: [Sync][Cleanup] Refactor SyncerError
entry.content:
SyncerError used to mostly replicate SyncProtocolErrorType and mixed in

few other unrelated enum values, this CL makes some adjustments to avoid

this:

1. SyncProtocolErrorType extended with commit-specific values (CONFLICT,

INVALID_MESSAGE).

2. SyncerError stores high-level enum (success, network error, http

error, protocol error, protocol violation) + details specific to the

error type.

3. HTTP_UNAUTHORIZED is no longer special cased as a dedicated enum

value (callers check http status code when they need to special case

it).

4. UNSET has no analogues in the new SyncerError. Success() is used as

a default value (their treatments where equivalent, see IsActualError()

in old SyncerError).



There should be no behavioral changes, except some strings in

chrome://sync-internals.



Bug: 1363089

whether the migration ran. This simplifies some tests.

difference between "default" and "enabled" anyway.

entry.title: Use strategy pattern to init DeviceAuthenticator
entry.content:
This CL is part of a bigger refactoring process of the

DeviceAuthenticator class.



In this CL, DeviceAuthParams class is added. With every instantiation of

a platform-specific device authenticator, a DeviceAuthParams object

needs to be passed to the factory.



DeviceAuthParams has two methods:

1. Get the DeviceAuthSource (this value is used to record metrics).

2. Get the authentication validity period. It should be always 60

seconds, except for the password manager menu, where it is 5 minutes,

and for incognito, where it is 0 seconds.

The current way of making that timer be 0 seconds/ 5 minutes is kind of

hacky, and both of the situations will be taken care of in future CL's,

so that DeviceAuthParams will be used to specify these timers.



Design doc for refactoring: http://docs/document/d/15E8t2BcmN241P-1xpLzYXwROrTzzb1-fS9LnXRnHRKc?resourcekey=0-MgxW9Z7T5rY5AzhcyTg__w#heading=h.xgjl2srtytjt .

entry.title: Include global ids in form and form field similarity checks.
entry.content:
FormDataAndroid::SimilarFormAs and its FormFieldDataAndroid sibling

serve one purpose: They are called to determine whether a form has

changed enough (e.g. between focus events or on user input) that it

should trigger restarting the ongoing Autofill session.



Using *only* FormGlobalId and FieldGlobalId is therefore not enough:

For example, form field may have changed its type completely, but

it would not be picked up by comparing ids alone.

On the other hand, global ids should be *part* of the similarity

check: Otherwise, there could be identical forms on a page, but

Android Autofill would not be able to distinguish them.

entry.title: [PA] Fix the loop condition for updating reservation offset table.
entry.content:
When updaring reservation offset table,

(1) Compare |address_start| with |address_end|.

If |address_start| < |address_end|, finish the loop.

Otherwise, go to (2).

(2) Update the table entry and

However, |address_start| + kSuperPageSize may overflow. E.g.

sizeof(uintptr_t)==4 and 0xffe00000 < |address_end|.

In the case, the loop will never end.

which is not possible with `GlyphForCharacter`.

runtime flag.

entry.title: [Promise Icons] Allow promise icons for reinstalled apps
entry.content:
Previously there was a bug where installing, uninstalling then

reinstalling an app would only create a promise icon when the app was

installed for the first time, but never for subsequent installations.

To fix that, this CL expands the check for a new app installation to

consider the various “uninstalled” statuses that apps can have while

registered in the AppRegistryCache. This will enable the installation

to be considered valid and eligible for a promise icon.

entry.title: Refactor externally managed installation flow
entry.content:
This CL has two main goals:

* Improving the readability of the installation flow and making

future changes easier to implement (DD [1]).

* Enabling in-place update of placeholder apps (DD [2]).



This is done by eliminating the split between installation tasks

and commands. This CL introduces a core `ExternalAppResolutionCommand`

command that is scheduled with a minimal lock when an externally

managed app should be installed. It loads all metadata and acquires

additional locks as needed and delegates functionality to sub jobs.

This part of the change implements no functionality change.



The 2nd part of this change implements in-place updates of placeholder

apps by checking in the `ExternalAppResolutionCommand` whether the app

id has changed and performs a migration if that is the case.



[1] https://docs.google.com/document/d/1B0HqAhv1nPq75qOtFtKNIiDrS0QjFUrYA3cKMONlRKE/edit?resourcekey=0-C053as2pQ5cdK_ixjTbw_Q#heading=h.5svp30dzbfrh
